04994nam a22005775i 9780822394327DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223943277 a10.1515/97808223943272doi  a(DE-B1597)553605  a(OCoLC)1167586257  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a303.609822200aAccounting for Violence :bMarketing Memory in Latin America /cKsenija Bilbija, Leigh A. Payne. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (424 p.) :b25 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Cultures and Practice of Violence00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword: On Memory and Memorials -- tIntroduction. Time is Money: The Memory Market in Latin America -- tA Prime Time to Remember: Memory Merchandising in Globo's Anos Rebeldes -- tAccounting for Murder: The Contested Narratives of the Life and Death of María Elena Moyano -- tTrauma Tourism in Latin America -- tThe Business of Memory: Reconstructing Torture Centers as Shopping Malls and Tourist Sites -- tMarketing and Sacred Space: The Parque de la Memoria in Buenos Aires -- tReading '68: The Tlatelolco Memorial and Gentrification in Mexico City -- tPromoting Peru: Tourism and Post-Conflict Memory -- tThe Moral Economy of Memory: Public and Private Commemorative Space in Post-Pinochet Chile -- tDress for Success: Fashion, Memory, and Media Representation of Augusto Pinochet -- tTortured by Fashion: Making Memory through Corporate Advertising -- tMemory Inventory: The Production and Consumption of Memory Goods in Argentina -- tConclusion. Marketing Discontent: The Political Economy of Memory in Latin America -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAccounting for Violence offers bold new perspectives on the politics of memory in Latin America. Scholars from across the humanities and social sciences provide in-depth analyses of the political economy of memory in Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Mexico, Peru, and Uruguay, countries that emerged from authoritarian rule in the 1980s and 1990s. The contributors take up issues of authenticity and commodification, as well as the "never again" imperative implicit in memory goods and memorial sites. They describe how bookstores, cinemas, theaters, the music industry, and television shows (and their commercial sponsors) trade in testimonial and fictional accounts of the authoritarian past; how tourist itineraries have come to include trauma sites and memorial museums; and how memory studies has emerged as a distinct academic field profiting from its own journals, conferences, book series, and courses. The memory market, described in terms of goods, sites, producers, marketers, consumers, and patrons, presents a paradoxical situation. On the one hand, commodifying memory potentially cheapens it. On the other hand, too little public exposure may limit awareness of past human-rights atrocities; such awareness may help to prevent their recurring.Contributors. Rebecca J. Atencio, Ksenija Bilbija, Jo-Marie Burt, Laurie Beth Clark, Cath Collins, Susana Draper, Nancy Gates-Madsen, Susana Kaiser, Cynthia E. Milton, Alice A. Nelson, Carmen Oquendo Villar, Leigh A. Payne, José Ramón Ruisánchez Serra, Maria Eugenia Ulfe  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCollective memoryzLatin America. 0aMemorialszLatin America. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectszLatin America. 0aViolencexSocial aspectszLatin America. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aBilbija, Ksenija, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPayne, Leigh A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part 